# {{non-gloss|Genitive case marker, chiefly for inanimate nouns.}}

=====Usage notes=====
In Middle Korean, the genitive case marker {{okm-inline|-ㅅ|-s}} was used for both inanimate nouns and honored animate nouns, while the other genitive marker {{okm-inline|-의〮|-úy}} was reserved for non-honored animate nouns.

In the limited Old Korean corpus, {{m|oko||叱|tr=*-s}} appears to be used chiefly for inanimate nouns. Meanwhile, many texts use the genitive {{m|oko|尸|tr=*-lq}}, with no evident Middle Korean reflex, for honored nouns such as the [[Buddha]]. There is a strong argument that {{m|oko|尸|tr=*-lq}} is an allomorphic variant of {{m|oko||叱|tr=*-s}}, representing a phenomenon ancestral to the tensing of the subsequent obstruent that occurred in Middle Korean when {{m|okm|-ㅅ}} occurred between a sonorant and an obstruent. If true, there was no distinction between Old and Middle Korean in the use of the genitive -s.

Unlike the other Old Korean genitive marker {{m|oko|衣|tr=*-uy}}, {{m|oko||叱|tr=*-s}} could follow other case markers.

